2 Strong links 001 This technique relies on Conjugate Pairs . The value 8 in block 6 and row 7 forms 2 (regional) strong links or conjugate pairs with 1 set(s) of bridge cells in column 7 and column 7 . The 2 strong links are joined therefore with 1 weak link(s). Any occurrence of the value 8 can be removed from any cells sharing a region or regions with both start and end cells r6c8 and r7c6 . This technique is closely related to 2x1 Finned Sashimi X-Wing technique logic, Coloring technique or L1-Wing technique. It is a subcategory of X-Chains group of techniques which is in itself a subgroup of Alternating Inference Chains (AIC) group of techniques. These use strong links in L ocation inferred from 1 value (L1), therefore, L1-Wing can be used to describe this pattern (Currently L1 is used with 3 strong links only).

Unique Rectangle type 1 The cells r2c1,r2c3,r7c3,r7c1 form a Unique Rectangle with the values 2 and 3 . There are exactly two ways of placing the values 2 and 3 in the cells of the Unique Rectangle, forming two possible configurations. In both configurations, each row, column or block touched by the Unique Rectangle contains each of the two values 2 and 3 exactly once. As a result, if one of these two configurations were part of the solution, it could then be replaced by the other one to get a second valid solution . Because a valid sudoku cannot have more than one solution, none of the two configurations of the Unique Rectangle can be valid. The only possible way to avoid these two configurations is if the cell r7c1 does not contain the values 2 and 3 .

VWXYZ-Wing 1412 The five cells r1c7 , r3c7 , r4c7 , r8c7 and r7c9 form a VWXYZ-Wing : The four cells r1c7 , r3c7 , r4c7 and r8c7 form an almost locked set linked to the bivalue cell r7c9 through the value 6 . If the value 3 was eliminated from all 4 cells of the Wing then the remaining value 6 in cell r7c9 would force the remaining 4 cells to have only 3 possible candidates to fill them. That is impossible! Other occurrences of the value 3 can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a row, column or block with all Wing cells containing the value 3 . The largest cell of the wing has 4 candidates and the 4 cells of the ALS have a total of 12 candidates.

UVWXYZ-Ring 2416 The six cells r1c8 , r2c8 , r2c7 , r2c9 , r3c8 and r4c8 form a double-linked UVWXYZ-Wing : The five cells r1c8 , r2c8 , r2c7 , r2c9 and r3c8 form an almost locked set linked to the bivalue cell r4c8 through both values 2 and 1 therefore creating a loop (ring). Regardless of the final value of cell r4c8 , the double-link would force the other 5 cells from the pattern to have different values to that one. The 6 different values will be in 6 cells therefore forming a locked set. Other occurrences of any of the values of the Ring pattern can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a row, column or block with all Ring cells containing that value. The largest cell of the Ring has 4 candidates and all 5 cells of the ALS have a total of 16 candidates. The pattern is similar to a 6digit-6cell Sue de Coq (SDC).

Skyscraper 011 This technique relies on Conjugate Pairs . The value 4 in column 2 and column 4 forms 2 (regional) strong links or conjugate pairs with 1 set(s) of bridge cells in row 9 and row 9 . The 2 strong links are joined therefore with 1 weak link(s). Any occurrence of the value 4 can be removed from any cells sharing a region or regions with both start and end cells r6c2 and r4c4 . This technique is closely related to 2x1 Finned Sashimi X-Wing technique logic, Coloring technique or L1-Wing technique. It is a subcategory of X-Chains group of techniques which is in itself a subgroup of Alternating Inference Chains (AIC) group of techniques. These use strong links in L ocation inferred from 1 value (L1), therefore, L1-Wing can be used to describe this pattern (Currently L1 is used with 3 strong links only).

Unique Rectangle type 4 The cells r1c8,r1c9,r5c9,r5c8 form a Unique Rectangle with the values 4 and 6 . There are exactly two ways of placing the values 4 and 6 in the cells of the Unique Rectangle, forming two possible configurations. In both configurations, each row, column or block touched by the Unique Rectangle contains each of the two values 4 and 6 exactly once. As a result, if one of these two configurations were part of the solution, it could then be replaced by the other one to get a second valid solution . Because a valid sudoku cannot have more than one solution, none of the two configurations of the Unique Rectangle can be valid. Note that the two cells r5c9 and r5c8 are the only possible positions of the value 4 in the row , thus, one of these two cells will contain the value 4 . Therefore, the only possible way to avoid the two configurations is if neither r5c9 nor r5c8 contains the value 6 .

XY-Wing The three cells r4c7 , r4c1 and r7c7 form an XY-Wing pattern on the value 1 . Regardless of the correct value of the cell r4c7 ( 7 or 8 ), one of the two cells r4c1 or r7c7 will have the value 1 as its only remaining possible value. It follows that either the cell r4c1 or the cell r7c7 must contain the value 1 . Other occurrences of the value 1 can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a row, column or block with both r4c1 and r7c7 .

WXYZ-Wing 126 The four cells r7c1 , r7c5 , r7c7 and r4c7 form an WXYZ-Wing : The three cells r7c1 , r7c5 , and r7c7 form an almost locked set linked to the bivalue cell r4c7 through the value 7 . If the value 8 was eliminated from all 4 cells of the Wing then the remaining value 7 in cell r4c7 would force the remaining 3 cells to have only 2 possible candidates to fill them. That is impossible! Other occurrences of the value 8 can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a row, column or block with all Wing cells containing the value 8 . The largest cell of the wing has 2 candidates and all 4 cells of the WXYZ-Wing pattern have a total of 6 candidates.

Unique Rectangle type 1 The cells r2c2,r3c2,r3c7,r2c7 form a Unique Rectangle with the values 3 and 9 . There are exactly two ways of placing the values 3 and 9 in the cells of the Unique Rectangle, forming two possible configurations. In both configurations, each row, column or block touched by the Unique Rectangle contains each of the two values 3 and 9 exactly once. As a result, if one of these two configurations were part of the solution, it could then be replaced by the other one to get a second valid solution . Because a valid sudoku cannot have more than one solution, none of the two configurations of the Unique Rectangle can be valid. The only possible way to avoid these two configurations is if the cell r2c7 does not contain the values 3 and 9 .

VWXYZ-Wing 1412 The five cells r9c1 , r9c3 , r9c5 , r9c8 and r7c7 form a VWXYZ-Wing : The four cells r9c1 , r9c3 , r9c5 and r9c8 form an almost locked set linked to the bivalue cell r7c7 through the value 6 . If the value 3 was eliminated from all 4 cells of the Wing then the remaining value 6 in cell r7c7 would force the remaining 4 cells to have only 3 possible candidates to fill them. That is impossible! Other occurrences of the value 3 can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a row, column or block with all Wing cells containing the value 3 . The largest cell of the wing has 4 candidates and the 4 cells of the ALS have a total of 12 candidates.

UVWXYZ-Ring 2416 The six cells r7c2 , r8c2 , r8c1 , r8c3 , r9c2 and r8c5 form a double-linked UVWXYZ-Wing : The five cells r7c2 , r8c2 , r8c1 , r8c3 and r9c2 form an almost locked set linked to the bivalue cell r8c5 through both values 9 and 1 therefore creating a loop (ring). Regardless of the final value of cell r8c5 , the double-link would force the other 5 cells from the pattern to have different values to that one. The 6 different values will be in 6 cells therefore forming a locked set. Other occurrences of any of the values of the Ring pattern can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a row, column or block with all Ring cells containing that value. The largest cell of the Ring has 4 candidates and all 5 cells of the ALS have a total of 16 candidates. The pattern is similar to a 6digit-6cell Sue de Coq (SDC).

Unique Rectangle type 1 The cells r2c2,r3c2,r3c7,r2c7 form a Unique Rectangle with the values 3 and 9 . There are exactly two ways of placing the values 3 and 9 in the cells of the Unique Rectangle, forming two possible configurations. In both configurations, each row, column or block touched by the Unique Rectangle contains each of the two values 3 and 9 exactly once. As a result, if one of these two configurations were part of the solution, it could then be replaced by the other one to get a second valid solution . Because a valid sudoku cannot have more than one solution, none of the two configurations of the Unique Rectangle can be valid. The only possible way to avoid these two configurations is if the cell r2c7 does not contain the values 3 and 9 .

2 Strong links 001 This technique relies on Conjugate Pairs . The value 7 in block 6 and row 7 forms 2 (regional) strong links or conjugate pairs with 1 set(s) of bridge cells in column 7 and column 7 . The 2 strong links are joined therefore with 1 weak link(s). Any occurrence of the value 7 can be removed from any cells sharing a region or regions with both start and end cells r6c8 and r7c6 . This technique is closely related to 2x1 Finned Sashimi X-Wing technique logic, Coloring technique or L1-Wing technique. It is a subcategory of X-Chains group of techniques which is in itself a subgroup of Alternating Inference Chains (AIC) group of techniques. These use strong links in L ocation inferred from 1 value (L1), therefore, L1-Wing can be used to describe this pattern (Currently L1 is used with 3 strong links only).

Grouped 3 Skyscrapers 1111 This technique relies on Conjugate Pairs that infer a strong link and/or a special arrangement of values in a line or block also known as Grouped Strong Links (where a strong link is inferred from groups of cells having the same value). These use strong links in L ocation inferred from 1 value (L1), therefore, Grouped L1-Wing can be used to describe this pattern.(Currently, L1 is reserved for 3 strong links). the arrangement of cells with value 1 in row 1, row 7 and row 6 form strong links (conjugate pairs, shown as green values) or grouped strong links (orange cell outline or yellow cell background). These strong links are weakly linked to each other via column 7 and column 6 (Red or Green outlined region). Any occurrence of the value 1 can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a region or regions with ALL cells with value 1 in row 1 and row 6 that are not part of column 7 or column 6 . This technique is part of more generalized technique called X- chains which in itself is part of more generalized technique called Alternating Inference Chains (AIC). This technique uses logic closely related to Finned Swordfish technique logic. The grouped strong link when inferred from cells in a block that are arranged in one mini-row and one mini-column is also known commonly as "Empty rectangle". The inference of a strong link from a group of cells with value 1 in any region can be spotted when a an "Empty mini Area (EmA)" is observed. This EmA could be an empty mini-Line (EmL) in a region or regions. In the case of "Empty rectangle" the EmA is a group of empty cells that can also be referred to as "Empty mini Rectangle (EmR)".

Forcing Chain If we assume that r7c6 contains the value 8, it follows, through a Forcing Chain, that r7c6 cannot contain the value 8. Therefore we can conclude that r7c6 does not contain the value 8 . The Forcing Chain consists of a chain of implications based on simple rules. The details of the Forcing Chain are given below. Details of the Forcing Chain: (1) If r7c6 contains the value 8, then r7c6 cannot contain the value 1 (the cell can contain only one value) (2) If r7c6 does not contain the value 1, then r7c7 must contain the value 1 (only remaining possible position in the row) (3) If r7c7 contains the value 1, then r1c7 cannot contain the value 1 (the value can occur only once in the column) (4) If r1c7 does not contain the value 1, then r1c7 must contain the value 7 (only remaining possible value in the cell) (5) If r1c7 contains the value 7, then r1c6 cannot contain the value 7 (the value can occur only once in the row) (6) If r1c6 does not contain the value 7, then r1c6 must contain the value 8 (only remaining possible value in the cell) (7) If r1c6 contains the value 8, then r7c6 cannot contain the value 8 (the value can occur only once in the column)

XY-Wing The three cells r4c4 , r5c6 and r8c4 form an XY-Wing pattern on the value 8 . Regardless of the correct value of the cell r4c4 ( 3 or 7 ), one of the two cells r5c6 or r8c4 will have the value 8 as its only remaining possible value. It follows that either the cell r5c6 or the cell r8c4 must contain the value 8 . Other occurrences of the value 8 can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a row, column or block with both r5c6 and r8c4 .

WXYZ-Wing 126 The four cells r4c4 , r4c5 , r5c6 and r2c6 form an WXYZ-Wing : The three cells r4c4 , r4c5 , and r5c6 form an almost locked set linked to the bivalue cell r2c6 through the value 8 . If the value 6 was eliminated from all 4 cells of the Wing then the remaining value 8 in cell r2c6 would force the remaining 3 cells to have only 2 possible candidates to fill them. That is impossible! Other occurrences of the value 6 can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a row, column or block with all Wing cells containing the value 6 . The largest cell of the wing has 2 candidates and all 4 cells of the WXYZ-Wing pattern have a total of 6 candidates.

2 Strong links 001 This technique relies on Conjugate Pairs . The value 8 in block 6 and row 7 forms 2 (regional) strong links or conjugate pairs with 1 set(s) of bridge cells in column 7 and column 7 . The 2 strong links are joined therefore with 1 weak link(s). Any occurrence of the value 8 can be removed from any cells sharing a region or regions with both start and end cells r6c8 and r7c6 . This technique is closely related to 2x1 Finned Sashimi X-Wing technique logic, Coloring technique or L1-Wing technique. It is a subcategory of X-Chains group of techniques which is in itself a subgroup of Alternating Inference Chains (AIC) group of techniques. These use strong links in L ocation inferred from 1 value (L1), therefore, L1-Wing can be used to describe this pattern (Currently L1 is used with 3 strong links only).

Grouped 3 Strong links 3012 This technique relies on Conjugate Pairs that infer a strong link and/or a special arrangement of values in a line or block also known as Grouped Strong Links (where a strong link is inferred from groups of cells having the same value). These use strong links in L ocation inferred from 1 value (L1), therefore, Grouped L1-Wing can be used to describe this pattern.(Currently, L1 is reserved for 3 strong links). the arrangement of cells with value 1 in block 8, row 4 and column 9 form strong links (conjugate pairs, shown as green values) or grouped strong links (orange cell outline or yellow cell background). These strong links are weakly linked to each other via column 4 and block 6 (Red or Green outlined region). Any occurrence of the value 1 can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a region or regions with ALL cells with value 1 in block 8 and column 9 that are not part of column 4 or block 6 . This technique is part of more generalized technique called X- chains which in itself is part of more generalized technique called Alternating Inference Chains (AIC). This technique uses logic closely related to Finned Swordfish technique logic. The grouped strong link when inferred from cells in a block that are arranged in one mini-row and one mini-column is also known commonly as "Empty rectangle". The inference of a strong link from a group of cells with value 1 in any region can be spotted when a an "Empty mini Area (EmA)" is observed. This EmA could be an empty mini-Line (EmL) in a region or regions. In the case of "Empty rectangle" the EmA is a group of empty cells that can also be referred to as "Empty mini Rectangle (EmR)".

UVWXYZ-Ring 2416 The six cells r1c8 , r2c8 , r2c7 , r2c9 , r3c8 and r4c8 form a double-linked UVWXYZ-Wing : The five cells r1c8 , r2c8 , r2c7 , r2c9 and r3c8 form an almost locked set linked to the bivalue cell r4c8 through both values 2 and 1 therefore creating a loop (ring). Regardless of the final value of cell r4c8 , the double-link would force the other 5 cells from the pattern to have different values to that one. The 6 different values will be in 6 cells therefore forming a locked set. Other occurrences of any of the values of the Ring pattern can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a row, column or block with all Ring cells containing that value. The largest cell of the Ring has 4 candidates and all 5 cells of the ALS have a total of 16 candidates. The pattern is similar to a 6digit-6cell Sue de Coq (SDC).

XY-Wing The three cells r7c1 , r2c1 and r8c3 form an XY-Wing pattern on the value 9 . Regardless of the correct value of the cell r7c1 ( 5 or 8 ), one of the two cells r2c1 or r8c3 will have the value 9 as its only remaining possible value. It follows that either the cell r2c1 or the cell r8c3 must contain the value 9 . Other occurrences of the value 9 can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a row, column or block with both r2c1 and r8c3 .

WXYZ-Wing 126 The four cells r7c1 , r7c2 , r8c3 and r5c3 form an WXYZ-Wing : The three cells r7c1 , r7c2 , and r8c3 form an almost locked set linked to the bivalue cell r5c3 through the value 9 . If the value 4 was eliminated from all 4 cells of the Wing then the remaining value 9 in cell r5c3 would force the remaining 3 cells to have only 2 possible candidates to fill them. That is impossible! Other occurrences of the value 4 can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a row, column or block with all Wing cells containing the value 4 . The largest cell of the wing has 2 candidates and all 4 cells of the WXYZ-Wing pattern have a total of 6 candidates.

Grouped 3 Skyscrapers 1111 This technique relies on Conjugate Pairs that infer a strong link and/or a special arrangement of values in a line or block also known as Grouped Strong Links (where a strong link is inferred from groups of cells having the same value). These use strong links in L ocation inferred from 1 value (L1), therefore, Grouped L1-Wing can be used to describe this pattern.(Currently, L1 is reserved for 3 strong links). the arrangement of cells with value 1 in row 1, row 7 and row 6 form strong links (conjugate pairs, shown as green values) or grouped strong links (orange cell outline or yellow cell background). These strong links are weakly linked to each other via column 7 and column 5 (Red or Green outlined region). Any occurrence of the value 1 can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a region or regions with ALL cells with value 1 in row 1 and row 6 that are not part of column 7 or column 5 . This technique is part of more generalized technique called X- chains which in itself is part of more generalized technique called Alternating Inference Chains (AIC). This technique uses logic closely related to Finned Swordfish technique logic. The grouped strong link when inferred from cells in a block that are arranged in one mini-row and one mini-column is also known commonly as "Empty rectangle". The inference of a strong link from a group of cells with value 1 in any region can be spotted when a an "Empty mini Area (EmA)" is observed. This EmA could be an empty mini-Line (EmL) in a region or regions. In the case of "Empty rectangle" the EmA is a group of empty cells that can also be referred to as "Empty mini Rectangle (EmR)".

Forcing Chain If we assume that r4c4 does not contain the value 1, it follows, through a Forcing Chain, that r4c4 must contain the value 1. Therefore we can conclude that r4c4 contains the value 1 . The Forcing Chain consists of a chain of implications based on simple rules. The details of the Forcing Chain are given below. There are exactly two ways of placing the values 5 and 8 in the cells of the Unique Rectangle, forming two possible configurations. In both configurations, each row, column or block touched by the Unique Rectangle contains each of the two values 5 and 8 exactly once. As a result, if one of these two configurations were part of the solution, it could then be replaced by the other one to get a second valid solution . Because a valid sudoku cannot have more than one solution, none of the two configurations of the Unique Rectangle can be valid. The only possible way to avoid these two configurations is if the cell r7c9 does not contain the values 5 and 8 .

WXYZ-Ring 249 The four cells r1c2 , r2c2 , r3c3 and r7c2 form a double-linked WXYZ-Wing : The three cells r1c2 , r2c2 , and r3c3 form an almost locked set linked to the bivalue cell r7c2 through both values 9 and 1 therefore creating a loop (ring). Other occurrences of any of the values of the Ring pattern can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a row, column or block with all Ring cells containing that value. The largest cell of the Ring has 4 candidates and all 4 cells of the WXYZ-Ring pattern have a total of 9 candidates. The pattern is similar to a 4digit-4cell Sue de Coq (SDC).

2 Strong links 001 This technique relies on Conjugate Pairs . The value 1 in block 4 and column 4 forms 2 (regional) strong links or conjugate pairs with 1 set(s) of bridge cells in row 5 and row 5 . This technique is closely related to 2x1 Finned Sashimi X-Wing technique logic, Coloring technique or L1-Wing technique. It is a subcategory of X-Chains group of techniques which is in itself a subgroup of Alternating Inference Chains (AIC) group of techniques. These use strong links in L ocation inferred from 1 value (L1), therefore, L1-Wing can be used to describe this pattern (Currently L1 is used with 3 strong links only).

Grouped Skyscraper 111 This technique relies on Conjugate Pairs that infer a strong link and/or a special arrangement of values in a line or block also known as Grouped Strong Links (where a strong link is inferred from groups of cells having the same value). These use strong links in L ocation inferred from 1 value (L1), therefore, Grouped L1-Wing can be used to describe this pattern.(Currently, L1 is reserved for 3 strong links). the arrangement of cells with value 9 in column 2 and column 9 form strong links (conjugate pairs, shown as green values) or grouped strong links (orange cell outline or yellow cell background). These strong links are weakly linked to each other via row 7 and row 7 (Red or Green outlined region). Any occurrence of the value 9 can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a region or regions with ALL cells with value 9 in column 2 and column 9 that are not part of row 7 or row 7 . This technique is part of more generalized technique called X- chains which in itself is part of more generalized technique called Alternating Inference Chains (AIC). This technique uses logic closely related to Finned X-Wing technique logic. The grouped strong link when inferred from cells in a block that are arranged in one mini-row and one mini-column is also known commonly as "Empty rectangle". The inference of a strong link from a group of cells with value 9 in any region can be spotted when a an "Empty mini Area (EmA)" is observed. This EmA could be an empty mini-Line (EmL) in a region or regions. In the case of "Empty rectangle" the EmA is a group of empty cells that can also be referred to as "Empty mini Rectangle (EmR)".

WXYZ-Wing 126 The four cells r7c1 , r7c3 , r8c2 and r2c2 form an WXYZ-Wing : The three cells r7c1 , r7c3 , and r8c2 form an almost locked set linked to the bivalue cell r2c2 through the value 9 . If the value 7 was eliminated from all 4 cells of the Wing then the remaining value 9 in cell r2c2 would force the remaining 3 cells to have only 2 possible candidates to fill them. That is impossible! Other occurrences of the value 7 can therefore be removed from any cells sharing a row, column or block with all Wing cells containing the value 7 . The largest cell of the wing has 2 candidates and all 4 cells of the WXYZ-Wing pattern have a total of 6 candidates.
